AT THE SAME TIME THE OTHER VEHICLE SWITCHED LANES CAUSING OUR TRUCK TO MAKE AND EMERGENCY STOP.  THE OTHER VEHICLE KEPT GOING.  THE SUDDEN STOP PUSHED A 55 GALLON DRUM OF HYDROGEN PEROXIDE INTO THE MEDIAN.  THE DRUM SUSTAINED A SMALL CRACK SPILLING ABOUT 25 GALLONS.  THERE WAS NO DAMAGE TO THE REST OF THE LOAD.  EMERGENCY CREW EVACUATED A NEARBY CONVENIENCE STORE AND CLOSED THE INTERSTATE.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND NO ONE WAS INJURED.

column168: SEQUENCE OF EVENTS  OUR DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE DELIVERY ADDRESS BEFORE THE FACILITY OPENED.  WHILE HE WAS WAITING FOR ACCESS TO THE DELIVERY LOCATION HE EXITED THE TRUCK AND STARTED PREPARING FOR THE DELIVERY.  HE OPENED THE VALVES AND PULLED THE DELIVERY HOSE PARTIALLY OFF THE REEL.  WHILE HE WAS PULLING THE HOSE, THE NOZZLE VALVE WAS KNOCKED OPEN.  HE THEN ENTERED THE TRUCK AND WAITED FOR SOMEONE TO SHOW UP.  WHEN HE SAW HIS CONTACT ARRIVE AND EXITED HIS CAR, MY DRIVER ENGAGED THE PUMP TO BEGIN HIS DELIVERY.  WHEN THE PUMP WAS ENGAGED, GASOLINE STARTED TO SPRAY OUT OF THE PARTIALLY OPENED NOZZLE.  THE EMPLOYEE THAT HAD JUST ARRIVED SAW LEAK AND NOTIFIED OUR DRIVER WHO DISENGAGED THE PUMP TO STOP THE SPILL.  ACTION TAKEN AT TIME OF DISCOVERY  BECAUSE THE AMOUNT OF THE SPILL SEEMED MINOR THE EMPLOYEE OF OUR CUSTOMER TOLD OUR DRIVER THAT HE WOULD CLEAN UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT.  OUR DRIVER MADE HIS DELIVERY AND LEFT.  WE WERE NOTIFIED THE FOLLOWING MORNING AND WENT OUT TO THE SITE TO BEGIN OUR INVESTIGATION.  BY THE TIME WE FOUND OUT ABOUT THE SPILL, THE CHICAGO FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD ALREADY CLEANED UP THE SITE.  DISCIPLINARY ACTION WAS TAKEN ON OUR EMPLOYEE FOR FAILURE TO REPORT THE SPILL.  ACTION TAKEN TO PREVENT FUTURE SPILLS  WE REEVALUATED THE PROCEDURES THAT OUR DRIVERS TAKE WHEN PREPARING FOR A DELIVERY AND FOUND THAT IF OUR DRIVER HAD FOLLOWED THE NORMAL STEPS OF OPENING THE VALVES AND THEN TAKING THE HOSE OFF THE REEL HE WOULD NOT HAVE BEEN IN A POSITION TO HAVE THE NOZZLE OPEN ACCIDENTLY, OR WOULD HAVE BEEN ABLE TO CLOSE THE NOZZLE IMMEDIATELY.  ALL OF OUR DRIVERS WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT AND INSTRUCTED TO FOLLOW THE PROPER PROCEDURES WHEN MAKING A DELIVERY.

DRIVER WAS TO DELIVER 7300 GALLONS OF #2 HEATING OIL TO UPPER MERION ADMINISTRATION BUILDING TANK ONE.  DRIVER STUCK THE TANKS AND DETERMINED THAT ONE TANK WAS FILLED AND THE OTHER HAD LESS THAN 1400 GALLONS.  THERE ARE 2 TANKS AT THIS LOCATION EACH WITH 10,000 CAPACITY AND THEY ARE UNDERGROUND.  THE FILLS ARE REMOTE AND ARE 30' UPHILL FROM THE TANKS.  THE RIGHT FILL IS MASKED NUMBER ONE AND THE LEFT FILL IS MARKED NUMBER TWO. THE SIGHT MANHOLE COVER IS NOT MARKED AND THE LEFT MANHOLE COVER IS MARKED NUMBER ONE.  THIS IS BECAUSE THE PIPING FOR THE TANKS IS BACKWARDS.  UPPER MERION HAD A UTILITY TRAILER PARKED OVER BOTH MANHOLE COVERS SO THE DRIVER COULD NOT SEE THE TANK MARKINGS.  DRIVER THEN STARTED TO DROP HEATING OIL INTO WHAT HE THOUGHT WAS THE CORRECT TANK BUT WAS ACTUALLY THE TANK THAT WAS FILLED.  HEATING OIL STARTED TO COME OUT OF THE VENT AND RUN DOWNHILL INTO A STORM DRAIN.  40 GALLONS WAS SPILLED.  DRIVER INSTALLED AN OIL BOOM IN STORM DRAIN.  CLEAN VENTURES INC. (856-365-5544).  REMOVE OIL FROM STORM DRAIN AND REMOVE ALL CONTAMINATED SOIL.  UPPER MERION HAS INSTALLED SIGNS THAT CORRECTLY IDENTIFY THE TANKS AND THE FILLS.  PETRON OIL HAS THE DELIVERY TICKETS MARKED THAT SHOW THE CORRECT TANKS AND FILLS.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: AMERICAN MOBILE PETROLEUM TANKER TRUCK #2 WAS INVOLVED IN A MINOR SPILL, ON JAN. 10, 2004 AT 7440 AVIATION PL. DALLAS, TX.  THE SPILL OCCURRED WHILE DRIVER MARK MCNUTT WAS TRYING TO SERVICE CUSTOMER GULFSTREAM AEROSPACE. AMP TRUCK IS EQUIPPED WITH A MANUAL FUEL PUMPING SYSTEM, WHILE TRYING TO TURN ON THE P.T.O (POWER TAKE OFF) DRIVER MARK MCNUTT NOTICED A LEAK ON THE NOZZLE.  HE IMMEDIATELY SHUT THE PUMP OFF, AND PROCEEDED TO FIND OUT WHAT CAUSED THE LEAKAGE IN THE NOZZLE.  AFTER CHECKING ALL SWITCHES AND PIPES AROUND THE TRUCK, HE WAS ENABLE TO FIND THE SOURCE OF THE PROBLEM.  IN AN EFFORT TO FOLLOW A.M.P. SAFETY GUIDELINES, MR. MCNUTT DECIDED IT WAS SAFER NOT TO SERVICE GULFSTREAM EQUIPMENT FOR THAT NIGHT.  AFTER SECURING HIS NOZZLE MR. MCNUTT PROCEEDED TOWARDS THE GATE AND LEFT THE PROPERTY.  ON JAN 12, 2004 GENERAL MANAGER SALIF NDIAYE RECEIVED A PHONE CALL FROM GULFSTREAM STATING THAT THERE WAS A STAIN AROUND ONE OF THEIR STORM DRAINS ON THEIR PROPERTY, AND IMPLIED THAT THE SECURITY GUARD ON DUTY FOR THE NIGHT OF JAN. 10, 2004 NOTICED FUEL ON THE GROUND AROUND THE STORM DRAIN AFTER AMP LEFT. MR. NDIAYE WENT OUT TO THE SPILL SITE.  AFTER THE INCIDENT WAS ACCESSED, MR. HDAIYE CALLED GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.  A GARNER PROJECT SUPERVISOR ARRIVED ON SITE AND MET WITH REPRESENTATIVES FROM THE CITY OF DALLAS STORM WATER MANAGEMENT DIVISION AND MR NDIAYE.  THE SPILL SCENARIO WAS THEN REVIEWED AND THE SPILL SITE WAS INSPECTED.  A GARNER VACUUM TRUCK ARRIVED ON SITE.  THEY STAINED AREA OF THE CONCRETE AND THE STORM DRAIN WERE TREATED WITH A MICROBIAL SOLUTION IN ORDER TO FURTHER ASSIST IN THE REMOVAL OF ANY HYDROCARBONS.  AN ESTIMATED 750 GALLONS OF RINSE WATER WAS REMOVED FROM THE STORM DRAIN.  AMP TRUCK #2 WAS SENT TO NORTH AMERICAN TRAILER FOR A VISUAL INSPECTION.  THE NOZZLE IN QUESTION WAS REPLACED AND ALL COMPONENTS ATTACHED TO THE TRUCK WERE RECERTIFIED.  DRIVER MARK MCNUTT ATTENDED A SAFETY CLASS TO FURTHER ASSIST HIM ON SAFETY GUIDELINES.

column168: 30 CU YD ROLLOFF CONTAINER WITH TOP TARP WAS LOADED ON DECK ON DROPDECK TRAILER.  DURING PROCESS OF UN LOADING A 30 CU YD ROLLOFF CONTAINER FROM THE FLOOR OF A DROP DECK TRAILER, THE CONTAINER SLID ON ICE THAT HAD FORMED ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER DUE TO WEATHER CONDITIONS.  THE CONTAINER SLID TO THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER AND FELL APPROX 2' TO THE CEMENT CONTAINMENT PAD.  UPON HITTING THE GROUND, A GAP WAS FORMED BETWEEN THE TOP SIDE OF THE CONTAINER AND THE TARP.  APPROXIMATELY 2 POUNDS OF MATERIAL SPILLED FROM THE CONTAINER INTO THE CONTAINMENT PAD.  IMMEDIATE ACTION WAS TAKEN TO THE TSD FACILITY AND THE TRANSPORTER'S EMPLOYEES TO SCRAPE UP THE SPILLED MATERIAL.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS THEN PROPERLY DISPOSED OF BY TSD EMPLOYEES.  THE CONTAINER WAS UPRIGHTED AND EMPTIED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  UPON RETURN TO THE TRANSPORTER'S FACILITY, THE TRAILER CONFIGURATION WAS REDESIGNED TO ADD RETENTION RAILS TO THE SIDES OF THE BED OF THE TRAILER TO PREVENT ROLLOFF CONTAINERS FROM SLIDING OFF THE SIDES.

column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: THE BOTTOM LOADING RACK AT THE CRANEY ISLAND FUEL DEPOT WAS DAMAGED DURING HURRICANE ISABELA AND HAD NOT BEEN REPAIRED.  AN EMERGENCY MAKE SHIFT LOADING STATION IS CURRENTLY BEING USED FOR LOADING TANK TRUCKS.  THE DRIVER CONNECTS A 30 FOOT RUBBER HOSE TO THE TRAILER BOTTOM LOADING HEAD THEN CLIMBS ON TOP OF THE TANKER AND OPENS THE APPROPRIATE COMPARTMENT DOME LID AND ATTEMPTS TO LOAD TO A CERTAIN MARKER INSIDE THE TANK.  THE CRANEY ISLAND FUEL SPECIALIST HAS TO GO INSIDE AN ADJACENT BUILDING, OPEN A ROTARY VALVE WHICH STARTS GRAVITY FLOW OF PRODUCT THEN MOVES TO THE REAR WALL AND TURNS ON THE PUMP SWITCH.  THERE ARE NO METERS TO INDICATE THE QUANTITY OF PRODUCT.  WHEN THE PRODUCT LEVEL REACHES A CERTAIN POINT INSIDE EACH COMPARTMENT THE DRIVER ON TOP OF THE TRAILER CALLS TO THE LOADER WHO MOVES INSIDE THE BUILDING, SHUTS OFF THE PUMP AND THEN CLOSES THE ROTARY VALVE. IN THIS ONE INSTANCE EITHER THE DRIVER FAILED TO NOTIFY THE LOADER SOON ENOUGH OR THE LOADER FAILED TO ACT QUICKLY ENOUGH.  IN ANY EVENT ABOUT 15 GALLONS OF JET FUEL CAME OUT OF THE OPEN DOME LID OF THE COMPARTMENT BEING LOADED BEFORE THE PRODUCT STOPPED FLOWING.  THERE WERE NO KNOWN EQUIPMENT FAILURES.  EVERY EFFORT IS BEING MADE TO LOAD TO THE LOWEST MARKERS INSIDE EACH COMPARTMENT IN ORDER TO PREVENT SIMILAR INCIDENTS.
DRIVER DISCONNECTED FROM FILL AND 2 DROPS SPILLED ONTO STONE FOUNDATION. DRIVER CLEANED WITH SIMPLE GREEN & RAGS.

THE LEAKING JUG AND THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTEEN GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE IN THE TERMINAL YARD, FREE PRODUCT WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER. UPON INVESTIGATION OF THE TRAILER BY BAYWEST ENVIRONMENTAL PERSONNEL ONE LEAKING THREE-HUNDRED AND FIFTY GALLON STEEL TOTE WAS DISCOVERED IN THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY THIRTY GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE VALVE.  BAYWEST ENVIRONMENTAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, ABSORBENTS AND ABSORBENT PADS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A TWENTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINING PRODUCT IN THE TOTE WAS PLACED INTO SEVEN, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTICS DRUMS.  ALL SEVEN DRUMS AND THE LEAKING TOTE WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING FURTHER INSTRUCTIONS. column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING ONE HUNDRED AND TWENTY GALLON PLASTIC TOTE WAS DISCOVERED AT ABOUT THE HALFWAY MARK OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND CONTAINED TO THE TRAILER.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LEAKING SEAM ON THE BOTTOM OF THE TOTE. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, TWENTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE TOTE WAS PLACED ON A RECOVERY PLATFORM.  ROADWAY, EXPRESS, INC. column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: THE IV TRAILER WAS BEING UNLOADED INTO THE CONSIGNEE'S STORAGE TANK AND THE TANK DOESN'T HAVE A VALVE OR A ONE WAY VALVE.  THE DISCHARGE HOSE IS HUNG OVER THE TOP OF THE STORAGE TANK AND SECURED.  WHEN THE IV DRIVER THROUGH THE PRODUCT WAS OFFLOADED HE DISCONNECTED HIS HOSE AND THE PRODUCT SPRAYED ON THE IV DRIVER AND ON THE TANK AND INTO A CONTAINMENT AREA ON THE CEMENT. THE CONSIGNEE RINSED IT DOWN WITH WATER INTO THEIR WASTE WATER TREATMENT SYSTEM.  THE IV DRIVER WAS TREATED BY THE CONSIGNEE'S PLANT NURSE.  THE IV DRIVER WENT TO THE EMERGENCY ROOM AND WAS TREATED AND RELEASE AND BACK TO WORK ON 01/19/2004.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: THE SHIPPER WAS LOADING THE IV TRAILER AND USING THE SHIPPER'S HOSES.  THE SHIPPER'S HOSE RUPTURED AND PRODUCT SPILLED ONTO THE IV TRAILER.  THE SHIPPER WASHED DOWN THE IV TRAILER.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: WHEN THE IV DRIVER WAS FINISHED UNLOADING INTO THE FIRST DROP AT THE CONSIGNEES AND WAS DISCONNECTED HIS HOSE, THE HOSE STILL HAD SOME AIR IN IT AND THE PRODUCT SPRAYED OUT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE'S WALL AND ONTO THE CONSIGNEE'S UNLOADER EMPLOYEE'S LIPS.  THE SUPERVISOR INSTRUCTED THE EMPLOYEE TO GET INTO THE SHOWER AND THEN PUT SOME VINEGAR ON THIS LIP. SOME PRODUCT ALSO GOT ONTO HIS COAT.  THE IV DRIVER WENT TO THE 2ND DROP AND FINISHED UNLOADING WITHOUT DIFFICULTY.  2 HOURS LATER THE IV DRIVER NOTICED ON HIS RIGHT WRIST HE HAD 3 SMALL BURNS FROM THE PRODUCT THAT HAD SPRAYED AT THE CONSIGNEE, MUST HAVE GOTTEN INSIDE HIS GLOVE.  THE CONSIGNEE WASHED DOWN THE WALL INTO A CONTAINMENT STORAGE.  BOTH THE INJURIES ARE MINOR AND DID NOT NEED MEDICAL ATTENTION.  NO LOST TIME FROM WORK.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: THE PVC VALVE ON THE TOP OF THE TRAILER LEAKED WHEN THE DRIVER PUT PRESSURE ON THE TRAILER.  IV DRIVER CLEANED SPILL.  DRIVERS TERMINAL WILL TRY TO GET SOMEONE OUT TO THE CONSIGNEE TO FIX THE VALVE SO THE DRIVER CAN UNLOAD.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: THE CONSIGNEE'S TANK OVERFLOWED WHEN THE IV DRIVER WAS FINISHED UNLOADING. APPROX 3 TO 4 GALLONS OF SPILLED FOAM OUT OF THE TANK INTO A CONTAINMENT AREA ON THE CEMENT.  THE CONSIGNEE CLEANED UP THE SPILL.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: THE IV DRIVER HAD A CONTAINMENT TRAY UNDER THE TRACTOR AND THE IV TRACTOR PACKING DRYED OUT AND NEEDED TO BE TIGHTENED.  APPROX 3 OZ SPILLED INTO A CONTAINMENT AREA ON THE CEMENT AND THE PRODUCT EVAPORATED.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: DOCK WORKER WENT TO SET BOX DOWN IN TRAILER.  BOX HAD A HOLE AND HE SET IT DOWN TO FAST CAUSING BOTTLE TO BREAK AND SPILL.  WE IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED SPILL WITH SAWDUST AND CARDBOARD.  TALKED AND COUNSELED DOCK WORKER ON PREVENTING FURTHER OCCURRENCES.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: EMPLOYEE SAID THIS WAS JUST FREAK THING.  HE WAS LOADING ONE OF HIS STORAGE TANKS W/ A RAIL CAR LOAD.  WHEN HE WAS FINISHED HE SHUT DOWN BOTH TANK AND RAIL CAR, HE BLED DOWN THE HOSE, EMPLOYEE SAID SOMETIMES THE LINE WILL HOLD A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID AND JUST RELEASE A SMALL PUFF OF VAPOR PROPANE. THIS TIME IT WAS LIQUID, EMPLOYEE FIGURES A SMALL AMOUNT WAS LEFT IN THE HOSE AND WHEN THE WARM AIR HIT, IT FORCED THE LIQUID UP; IT HAPPENED SO FAST EMPLOYEE DID NOT HAVE A CHANCE TO GET OUT OF THE WAY.  EMP SOUGHT TREATMENT THE NEXT DAY.  THE DR. CLEANED AND DRESSED.  NO EVAC, NO ROAD CLOSURES.
LOADER HIT BOX WITH TIRE OF FORKLIFT WHILE LOADING CAUSING DDM TO 1 LITER OF ACID.

column168: DRIVER WAS UNLOADING INTO 8000 GALLON UNDERGROUND TANK.  HE HAD MISCALCULATED HIS OUTAGE IN UST AND OVERFILLED THE TANK CAUSING THE SPILL. SPILL WAS CONTAINED ON ASPHALT SURFACE.  PHILLIPS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES RESPONDED AND CLEANED UP SPILL UNDER DIRECTION OF SCDHEC.

A JEFF FOSTER TRUCKING DRIVER WAS DELIVERING #1 FUEL OIL TO ONE OF THE ABOVE-GROUND STORAGE TANKS LOCATED IN OUR HIBBING BULK PLANT.  THE TANK CAME FULL AND OVERFLOWED INTO THE TANK CONTAINMENT AREA.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED BY OUR PERSONNEL.  TANK GAUGES WILL BE CHECKED TO MAKE SURE THAT THEY ARE GIVING ACCURATE PRODUCT LEVELS.

column168: 1-12-04 AT 0750 HRS. A VENTING TANK CAR REPORT WAS RECEIVED BY TRAIN MASTER WHO INSPECTED YARD AND FOUND CAR # NPCX 000270 LOADED WITH ETHYLENE REF LIQUID TO BE VENTING: WAY BILL INFO CAR WAS LOADED BY EQUISTAR CHEMICAL CO. HAZ CLASS 2.1 FLAMMABLE GAS UN1038. CONTENTS WERE THEN SOLIDIFIED USING A CLAY BASED ABSORBENT AND PROCESSED THROUGH DMP.  NON-CONTAMINATED PRODUCT WAS RETURNED TO SHIPPER VIA A SALVAGE DRUM.

RESPONDER CALLED BECAUSE PACKAGE WAS LEAKING IN THE PRIMARY SORT.  TWO OF TEN BOTTLES WERE LEAKING DUE TO EXTREME COLD 12 DEGREES.  LIQUID WAS SUPPOSED TO BE STORED 35 - 90 DEGREES ALL LIQUID, CARDBOARD & GLOVES WERE PROCESSED THROUGH DMP.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: THE PACKAGE WAS CONTAINED.  PACKAGE WAS REMOVED FROM AREA TO THE DMP AREA. DAMAGED PRODUCT DISPOSED OF USING THE DMP PROGRAM.  CLEANED AND STORED THE EQUIPMENT.
PACKAGE DAMAGED AT UPS.  PKG WAS REFUSED BY SHIPPER SO IT WAS THEN PROCESSED THRU THE DMP PROGRAM.  CLEANED AND STORED THE EQUIPMENT.
PACKAGE DISCOVERED LEAKING DURING SORT.  LEAKAGE FROM APPARENTLY DEFECTIVE VALVE.  PACKAGE REMOVED TO OUTSIDE AND SECURED.  RECIPIENT CONTACTED TO PICKUP CYLINDER.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: PACKAGE DAMAGED BY OTHER FREIGHT DURING LOADING.  PACKAGE PLACED INTO STEEL SALVAGE DRUM.  SHIPPER CONTACTED FOR PACKAGE DISPOSITION.

column42: PRINTING INK, FLAMMABLE OR PRINTING INK RELATED MATERIAL (INCLUDING PRINTING INK THINNING OR REDUCING COMPOUND), FLAMMABLE
column168: THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE DAMAGE LEADING TO THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL OCCURRED.  THE ITEM WAS APPARENTLY DROPPED IN HANDLING.  THIS CAUSED BOTH INNER AND OUTER UNITS TO RUPTURE ALLOWING THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE CONTAINER WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE SHIPPER FOR DISPOSITION.

THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE OUTBOUND SORT AND RELOAD WHEN THE LEAKAGE COMING FROM THE CONTAINER WAS NOTICED. THE SHIPMENT WAS ISOLATED, OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL A SMALL RUST HOLE AT THE BOTTOM OF THE CONTAINER WHICH ALLOWED THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE CONTAINER WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELP PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE SHIPPER FOR DISPOSITION.

column168: ON 1/29/04, APPROXIMATELY 0920 HOURS, TANK CAR ACFX 82775 WAS OBSERVED LEAKING DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS ON PRESIDENTS ISLAND.  FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE MANWAY GASKET HAD BEEN PINCHED CAUSING IT TO BREAK AND GAP OPEN ABOUT ONE HALF INCH.  REPLACED THE GASKET WITH A NEW GASKET USED FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS.  THE CAR WAS OKAYED TO SPOT INTO THE CUSTOMER'S FACILITY AT 1130 HOURS.

THE MATERIAL HANDLER WAS MOVING, VIA FORKLIFT, 4 DRUMS ON A PALLET. WHILE BACKING TOWARD THE DOOR TO PUT THESE DRUMS INTO STORAGE, HE HIT A METAL 55-GALLON DRUM WITH METAL LIDS IN IT. ONE OF THE DRUMS ON THE PALLET FELL OFF, HITTING THE GRATING AND THE LID BROKE SPILLING ABOUT 45 GALLONS OF THE WASTE INTO THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT BELOW THE GRATING THE TEMPERATURE WAS NEAR ZERO DEGREES F. AS SOON AS APPROPRIATE PPE WAS DETERMINED ABSORBENT AND SHOVELS WERE USED TO MOVE THE WASTE, ALONG WITH THE DAMAGED DRUM INTO AN 85- GALLON SALVAGE DRUM. THE REST OF THE DRUMS OF THIS TYPE WERE MOVED ONE DRUM AT A TIME INTO STORAGE. THE CONTRACTOR THAT SUPPLIED THE DRUMS WAS INFORMED THAT THIS SK BRANCH WOULD NO LONGER ACCEPT THAT TYPE OF DRUM FOR THIS TYPE OF WASTE.

THE CAR WAS BEING DELIVERED FROM CSX TRANSPORTATION ON Q53520. THE LEAK WAS CONTAINED, THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND A SPILL RESPONSE CONTRACTOR RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL, CONTRACTOR PERSONNEL FOUND THE CAR DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM THE STEM OF THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. CONTRACTOR PERSONNEL ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN FOUR BOLTS ON THE SECUREMENT PLATE FOR THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. THREE BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED, BUT THE FOURTH BOLT'S THREADS WERE STRIPPED AND THE BOLT COULD NOT BE TIGHTENED. ARRANGEMENTS WERE THEN MADE FOR PRODUCT TRANSFER. ON THURSDAY, JANUARY 22, 2004 PRODUCT FROM GETX 3004 WAS TRANSFERRED INTO TANK TRUCKS AND SENT ON THE CONSIGNEE.

column168: ON JANUARY 25, 2004 AT THE CSX YARD IN ERWIN, TN, CSX PERSONNEL OBSERVED GATX 22290, A LOADED TANK CAR OF POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE, LEAKING FROM MANWAY WHEN MOVED. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED, THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND A RESPONSE CONTRACTOR RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. UPON ARRIVAL CONTRACTOR PERSONNEL FOUND MANWAY GASKET BOLTS LOOSE AND THE GASKET SHIFTED. THE GASKET WAS REPOSITIONED AND THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED,  AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION.

ACFX 77602, LOAD TURPENTINE, WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE TOP WHILE SITTING STILL AT CSX TRANSPORTATON'S MONCRIEF YARD IN JACKSONVILLE, FL CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT RESPONDED A HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER AND AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO REPAIR THE LEAK. THE CAR WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING LIQUID PRODUCT FROM THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE AND POSSIBLY AROUND THE MANWAY COVER AS THE CAR WAS SITTING STILL. THE CAR WAS SHELL FULL APPROXIMATELY 1700 GALLONS OF PRODUCTS WAS OFF LOADED FROM THE TANK CAR TO PROVIDE SUFFICIENT OUTAGE TO ALLOW FOR PRODUCT EXPANSION. THE OFF LOADED PRODUCT WAS DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE, IFF BY TRUCK ON 01-28-04. THE SHIPPER, BOWATER CANADIAN FOREST PRODUCTS, WAS NOTIFIED OF THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT.

CSX TRANSPORTATON'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED THAT 20FT CONTAINER, FSCU 737637, LOADED WITH 72 DRUMS OF TERPENE HYDROCARBONS, NOS (ORANGE OIL) WAS DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM ONTO FLATCAR VTTX922134, AT CSXT'S DUVAL YARD IN JACKSONVILLE, FL.  CSXT RESPONDED A HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER AND AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO THE YARD.  THE CONTRACTOR PLACED SORBENT PADS UNDER THE CONTAINER TO CONTAIN THE DRIPS AND THE FLATCAR WAS MOVED INTO CSX INTERMODAL'S TERMINAL TO LIFT THE CONTAINER OFF THE FLATCAR.  THE CONTAINER WAS LOADED WITH LOADED WITH 72, 55-GALLON STEEL DRUMS DOUBLE STACKED.  THE DRUMS HAD SHIFTED BECAUSE THERE WAS A VOID SPACE IN THE REAR OF THE CONTAINER WITH INSUFFICIENT BRACING TO SECURE THE LOAD.  THE CONTAINER WAS LIFTED OFF THE FLATCAR AND PLACED ON PLASTIC.  THE DRUMS WERE UNLOADED, INSPECTED AND SET ASIDE.  THREE DRUMS IN THE NOSE WERE DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING PRODUCT.  TWO HAD HOLES RUBBED INTO THEIR SIDEWALLS NEAR THE TOP RIM.  THESE WERE PLACED INTO 85 GALLOON OVER PACK DRUMS.  THE THIRD DRUM HAD A SMALL CRACK IN THE HEAD.  AN EPOXY SEALANT WAS USED TO PATCH AND SEAL THE CRACK.  THE CONTAINER WAS DECONTAMINATED AND THE DRUMS INCLUDING THE 2 OVER PACK DRUMS WERE RELOADED.  THE CONTAINER WAS BLOCKED AND BRACED ACCORDING TO RECOMMENDED PROCEDURES.  THE DOORS WERE SEALED AND THE CONTAINER WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

THE TOTE THAT WAS DEFECTIVE WAS ISOLATED AND THE VALVE WAS SEALED IN PLASTIC.  ALL THE CONTAMINATION FROM THE VESSEL WAS PLACED IN PLASTIC CONTAINERS AND REMOVED FROM THE VESSEL.  THE CONTAMINATED CONTAINER WAS CLEANED OF RESIDUE.  THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS AN "O" RING THAT WASN'T SEATED IN THE DISCHARGE VALVE HANDLE.

ON JANUARY 27, 2004, T.A.G. UNIT T9914 WAS HEADING WESTBOUND ON I-40; AT MILE MARKER 67, OUR DRIVER STARTED COUGHING/CHOKING ON SOME COFFEE AND BLACKED OUT.  OUR TRUCK VEERED INTO THE MEDIUM CROSSED THE EASTBOUND LANE AND WENT OFF AN EMBANKMENT CAUSING BOTH THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER TO TIP ON THEIR RIGHT SIDE.  FIRST, OUR CO-DRIVER CALLED BNFL'S PPS EMERGENCY PHONE NUMBER.  SECOND, 911 WAS CALLED TO DISPATCH THE POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENT. THE CO-DRIVER INFORMED THEM OF WHAT KIND OF MATERIAL WAS INVOLVED IN THE ACCIDENT AND REPORTED NO INJURIES AND THAT NO OTHER VEHICLES WERE INVOLVED. CONTACTED NEXT WAS AUBREY JONES, DIRECTOR OF OPERATIONS AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE COORDINATOR FOR T.A.G. TRANSPORT.  MR. JONES MADE SURE THE POLICE HAD BEEN CONTACTED.  HE THEN SPOKE WITH CORPORAL BEN CROSS, AN ARKANSAS STATE POLICE OFFICER, WHO INDICATED THAT THE ARKANSAS STATE DEPARTMENT OF SAFETY AND HEALTH HAD BEEN CONTACTED AND A HAZMAT EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WAS IN ROUTE TO THE SCENE.  MR. JONES THEN CONTACTED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER OF THE U.S. DOT AND PROCEEDED BY PHONING THE SHIPPER, JOHN WEST, FROM BNFL, INC.  MACK WRIGHT FROM THE DEPARTMENT OF ENERGY (DOE) WAS MADE AWARE OF THE ACCIDENT.  MR. JONES ALSO PHONED GARY A KINDRICK, PRESIDENT OF T.A.G. TRANSPORT, INC., AND INFORMED HIM OF THE SITUATION AND ACTIONS THAT WERE TAKEN.  FOLLOWING THE ACCIDENT, OUR DRIVER WAS TESTED FOR CONTROLLED SUBSTANCES AND ALCOHOL IN ACCORDANCE WITH 49 CFR AND COMPANY POLICY. PREVENTIVE ACTIONS TAKEN:  UPON ARRIVAL AT T.A.G. TRANSPORT, INC., A PANELED COMPANY PHYSICIAN SAW BOTH DRIVER AND CO-DRIVER.  OUR CO-DRIVER WAS TREATED FOR MINOR INJURIES.  THE DRIVER WAS EXAMINED TO DISCOVER IF THE BLACKOUT WAS MEDICALLY RELATED AND THUS, IF HE WAS ABLE TO RETURN TO WORK. DRIVER'S ABILITY TO RETURN TO WORK IS PENDING HIS PHYSICIAN'S MEDICAL RELEASE.

column168: ON JANUARY 7, 2004, WE WERE SCHEDULED TO DILUTE A TRUCKLOAD OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID (HCI).  THE LOAD WAS BEING TRANSPORTED BY SYSTEM TRANSPORT, AND WAS THE FIRST DILUTION WE WERE DOING ON BEHALF OF JONES-HAMILTON.  PRIOR TO THE ARRIVAL OF THE TRUCK, ONE OF TITAN'S TRANSLOADERS SECURED OUR UNLOADING ASSEMBLY AND AIR VALVE TO THE RAIL CAR.  WHEN THE TRUCK ARRIVED, WE FIRST TRANSFERRED THE WATER TO THE TRAILER.  NEXT, WE HOOKED THE ACID HOSES TO THE TRAILER AND BEGAN TO TRANSLOAD THE HCI.  AT THE END OF THE TRANSFER PROCESS, OUR TRANSLOADER DISCOVERED THAT HE HAD FAILED TO ATTACH THE PORTION OF THE UNLOADING ASSEMBLY THAT WOULD ALLOW HIM TO SEAL OFF THE RAIL CAR WHILE CLEARING THE TRANSFER HOSES.  HE THEN MADE THE DECISION TO DEPRESSURIZE THE RAIL CAR AND BLOW AIR FROM THE TRAILER TO THE CAR TO RID THE HOSES OF THE REMAINING ACID.  UNFORTUNATELY WHILE DOING THIS, WE EXPERIENCED AN EXCESSIVE BUILD UP OF AIR PRESSURE IN OUR TRANSFER PUMP WHICH CRACKED ITS HOUSING.  AS A RESULT, ROUGHLY 12 TO 15 GALLONS OF ACID SPILLED ONTO THE PAVEMENT.  THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED, AND OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WAS NOTIFIED.  THE SPILL WAS NEUTRALIZED AND CLEANED, AND THE WASTE GENERATED IN THE PROCESS WAS DISPOSED OF IN ACCORDANCE WITH LOCAL ENVIRONMENTAL REGULATIONS.  TO PREVENT THIS MISTAKE FROM HAPPENING IN THE FUTURE, WE HAD A TRAINING SESSION WITH THE TRANSLOADERS THAT ADDRESSED THE FOLLOWING POINTS: 1. THE PUMP USED IN THE TRANSFER OF THE HCI IS DESIGNED TO PERMIT THE PASSAGE OF PRODUCT AND AIR IN ONLY ONE DIRECTION.  THIS DIRECTION IS FROM THE RAIL CAR TO THE TRUCK, NOT THE TRUCK TO THE CAR.  THE PROPER FITTINGS MUST BE ATTACHED TO THE RAIL CAR IN ORDER FOR US TO SAFELY AND COMPLETELY CLEAR THE TRANSFER HOSES ONCE THE TRANSLOAD IS DONE.  3. WHENEVER FACED WITH AN UNUSUAL SITUATION, CALL A SUPERVISOR FOR HIS INPUT.  IT IS LIKELY THAT A MORE EXPERIENCED TRANSLOADER WOULD HAVE PREVENTED THIS ACCIDENT FROM HAPPENING.

ON 1/14/2004 AT 0058 A LEAKING SHIPMENT WITH AN ODOR OF PERFUME WAS REPORTED IN "K" BUILDING (SECONDARY 8) OF OUR MAIN SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177. PARTTIME SPILL TECHNICIANS TIMOTHY HINES AND CHRISTI COX DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE. THEY REMOVED THIS BOX FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION. UPON INVESTIGATION THEY FOUND THE BOX TO CONTAIN 9 X PLASTIC BOXES THAT EACH CONTAINED 1 X 3.4 OZ GLASS BOTTLE WITH A PUMP SPRAY TYPE CLOSURE OF "AMERICAN IDOL" PERFUME. THE LABEL ON EACH OF THESE GLASS BOTTLES STATED "FLAMMABLE" THE CLOSURES ON THESE BOTTLES WERE NOT SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS. THE CLOSURE ON SEVEN OF THESE BOTTLES WAS BROKEN ALLOWING EACH ONE TO LEAK ITS ENTIRE CONTENTS OF 3.4 OZ. THE PARTTIME SPILL TECHNICIANS REPLACED THE ITEMS BACK INTO THE BOX, SEALED AND BAGGED THE SHIPMENT IN TWO PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED IT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM. THIS SHIPMENT WAS HELD IN THE HAZMAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION. THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT MARKED OR LABELED AND DID NOT HAVE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING IT TO INDICATE THAT THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. THERE WERE SIXTEEN EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR. THEY WERE ADVISED WHAT THE ODOR WAS AND RETURNED TO THEIR WORK AREAS. NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED. NO FURTHER FOLLOW UP NEEDED. CLEAR OF SCENE 0129 THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE AT THE HAZMAT OFFICE IN WILMINGTON OHIO.

column168: UPON OFFLOADING THE FREIGHT THE BOX WAS FOUND TO HAVE LEAKED. THE BOX WAS OPENED TO REVEAL TWO CANS. ONE 4L CAN AND ONE SMALLER CAN. NEITHER CAN HAD POSITIVE CLOSURE. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND HELD PENDING AN MSDS. I CALLED THE SHIPPER, JOHN SCALA WHO INFORMED ME IT WAS LATEX PAINT. WHEN I INQUIRED FURTHER HE SAID IT WAS TO BE USED ON A BOAT. BASED ON MY EXPERIENCE, I KNOW IT'S LUDICROUS TO TRY TO USE LATEX PAINT ON A BOAT. I CALLED THE DEVOE PAINT DEALER IN BAY CITY, NY, PETE & SONS. I REQUESTED A COPY OF THE MSDS FOR A PRODUCT IDENTIFIED BY THE SHIPPER AS "ANTI-RUST 236" THOSE MSDS WERE FAXED TO ME. THE FLASHPOINTS FOR EACH THE OF THE COMMODITIES ARE 100 DEGREES F. I'VE FAXED THOSE MSDS TO SA KEVIN FITZPATRICK, MIA FAA. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS OR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED. THE FREIGHT HAS BEEN INSPECTED BY AGENT FITZPATRICK. THE SHIPPER LED FEDEX PERSONNEL TO BELIEVE THE FREIGHT WAS WATER-BASED WHEN IT WAS OFFERED IN BROOKLYN AT A FEDX-MANNED LOCATION. AS ALREADY MENTIONED IT IS A FACT A CLASS 3, PACKING GROUP III. TWO ASSOCIATED PACKAGES ARE BEING HELD AT THE FEDEX STATION, NASSAU BAHAMAS, FOR THE FAA.

UNITED AIRLINES PASSENGER CHECKED A BAG FOR HIS TRIP TO PORTLAND, OR.  THE CHECK LUGGAGE WAS BEING INSPECTED BY TSA IN THE BAGROOM OF UNITED AIRLINES WHEN IT ALARMED IN THE L-3 SCANNER.  THE LUGGAGE WAS TAKEN TO THE NEXT TSA INSPECTION STATION, A TSA EMPLOYEE OPENING THE BAG AND REMOVED A SMALL PLASTIC BOTTLE WITH DUCT TAPE ON THE TOP.  WHEN THE TSA EMPLOYEES PLACED THE BOTTLE ON THE METAL TABLE, THE BOTTLE LEAKED A SILVER LOOKING MATERIAL FROM THE TOP.  THE TSA EMPLOYEE CALLED FOR HIS SUPERVISOR WHO ALSO CALLED FOR A GSC.  UPON ARRIVING IN THE BAGROOM I WAS MEET BY TSA SUPERVISOR AT THE SPILL LOCATION.  AT THAT TIME WE CALLED FOR THE BWI AIRPORT FIRE DEPT TO LOOK AT THE SPILL AS WE BOTH THOUGHT THE MATERIAL WAS MERCURY.  THE FIRE DEPT AGREED WITH US AND HAD THE BAGROOM EVACUATED UNTIL THE MARYLAND DEPT OF ENVIRONMENTAL AND BALTIMORE COUNTY FIRE DEPT ARRIVED TO CLEAN UP THE 1/2 OZ OF MERCURY.  UNITED AIRLINES CALLED THE DEPT OF TRANSPORTATION (MR. MCLEMORE) CASE NUMBER #711167, FAA (STEVEN JOSEPH) TO MAKE SURE THEY KNEW OF THE TSA SPILL PROBLEM.  THE BAGROOM WAS CLOSED FOR 3 1/2 HOURS FOR CLEANING AND RETURN BACK TO UNITED AIRLINES.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1115 HOURS, 1-7-04, KEITH MCJUNKINS, AN APRIA HEALTHCARE EMPLOYEE, DRIVING A 2001 ISUZU, FRR, BOX TRUCK, UNIT #21054P, WAS INVOLVED IN AN UNINTENTIONAL REASON OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID, AT 705 FIERO LANE, SAN LUIS OBISPO, CA.  MCJUNKINS WAS IN THE PROCESS OF LEAVING THE APRIA FACILITY TO START HIS DELIVERY ROUTE WHEN HE HEARD A NOISE COMING FROM WHAT APPEARED TO BE INSIDE THE CARGO BOX ON HIS TRUCK.  HE PARKED THE VEHICLE AT THE CURB, SET THE EMERGENCY FLASHERS AND PROCEEDED TO THE SIDE DOOR OF THE BOX.  UPON OPENING THE DOOR HE DISCOVERED THAT AN H-TANK, CONTAINING OXYGEN, COMPRESSED HAD FALLEN INTO THE NON-SPECIFICATION CRYOGENIC CARGO TANK, CONTAINING OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID, MOUNTED IN THE VEHICLE. IN FALLING ON THE CARGO TANK THE H-TANK HAD BROKEN THE PRESSURE GAUGES AND OXYGEN WAS VENTING INTO THE INTERIOR OF THE BOX.  THE VENTED OXYGEN WAS EVAPORATING AT A RATE THAT PREVENTED ANY OXYGEN FROM ESCAPING IN LIQUID TO FORM.  THE IMMEDIATE AREA WAS SECURED AND THE SAN LUIS OBISPO FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CONTACTED.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND STOOD BY UNTIL THE VENTING PROCESS HAD BEEN COMPLETED AND THE OXYGEN DISBURSED.  ONCE THE FIRE DEPARTMENT DECLARED THE SCENE SAFE THE TRUCK AND LOAD WERE EXAMINED.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE H-TANK HAD BEEN IMPROPERLY SECURED IN THE VEHICLE PRIOR TO MOVEMENT.  THE H-TANK WAS SECURED AND THE VEHICLE WAS THEN MOVED TO THE APRIA PARKING LOT AND PLACED OUT OF SERVICE PENDING REPAIRS.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES, NO COLLATERAL DAMAGE, NOR WAS CLEAN UP REQUIRED.

APPARENTLY THE VALVE STEM ON THE TORCH INITIATED ALLOWING A BUILDUP OF PRESSURE ON THE INSIDE OF THE BOX WHICH BUILT UP TO SUCH A POINT THAT THE PACKAGE RUPTURED FROM THE INSIDE.  THERE WAS NO FIRE HAZARD IMMEDIATELY NOTICED IN THIS INCIDENT.  A PACKAGE HANDLER, JULIO RODRIGUEZ WAS SLIGHTLY INJURED AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT.  THERE WERE NO HAZMAT MARKINGS OR LABELS EXHIBITED ON THE OUTER SURFACE OF THE PACKAGE NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS OFFERED WITH THE SHIPMENT. column168: AT 12:00 PM ON JANUARY 15, 2004 SET ENVIRONMENTAL RECEIVED A CALL FROM JUBAL DUDLEY, ONE OF OUR SET DRIVERS THAT A SPILL OCCURRED INSIDE HIS TRAILER DURING HIS EN-ROUTE DELIVERY RUN TO OUR SET HOUSTON FACILITY.  MR. DUDLEY WAS TRAVELING ON HWY 45 IN CONROE TX WHEN A DRIVE BY PASSENGER INFORMED HIM WITH HAND SIGNALS THAT HIS TRAILER WAS APPARENTLY LEAKING SOME KIND OF FLUID.  MR. DUDLEY PULLED OVER OFF THE HIGHWAY ROADSIDE AT MILE MARKER 97 AND HWY 45 AND ASSESSED THE TRAILERS CONTENTS.  WHEN CHECKING INSIDE HIS TRAILER, MR. DUDLEY DISCOVERED A LEAKING TOTE TANK BELONGING TO TERIS (HEAT TREATMENT).  THE FREE PRODUCT LEAKED THROUGH A FAULTY VALVE ON THE TOTE AND WAS RELEASED ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  THE MATERIAL SPILLED WAS ALSO RELEASED THROUGH THE TRAILER AND ONTO THE HIGHWAY ASPHALT. THE TOTE HAD RELEASED ALL OF ITS CONTENTS AND WAS EMPTY WHEN MR. DUDLEY DISCOVERED IT.  MR. DUDLEY MADE AN EMERGENCY CALL INTO THE SET ENVIRONMENTAL HOME BASE FACILITY IN TOM BEAN TX AND REPORTED THE INCIDENT AND REQUESTED THAT A CREW BE DISPATCHED OUT TO HELP ASSIST IN THE CLEANUP OF HIS TRAILER AND ROADSIDE.  MIKE UNCAPHER OF SET WAS ASSIGNED ER SUPERVISOR FOR THE SPILL AND WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SPILL SITE WITH SET TECHNICIANS JACOB BODDIE AND JAMES DIXON.  THE APPROPRIATE SUPPLIES AND ABSORBENT MATERIALS WERE LOADED AND STOCKED IN THE ER JOB TRAILER.  THE CREW DEPARTED THE TOM BEAN YARD AT APPROXIMATELY 12:45 PM AND HEADED OUT TO MEET MR. DUDLEY AND ASSESS HIS SPILL LOCATION IN CONROE, TX.  THE CREW ARRIVED ON SITE AT 3:45 PM AND WAS MET BY MR. DUDLEY.  SET CONDUCTED A TAILGATE SAFETY MEETING AND ER SUPERVISOR, MIKE UNCAPHER SPOKE WITH TXDOT ABOUT THE CLEANUP PROCEDURES AND SET'S PLAN OF ATTACK.  THE CREW THEN DONNED A LEVEL C PPE ENTRY AND ENTERED THE HOT ZONE INSIDE THE TRAILER TO PERFORM AN ASSESSMENT OF THE AFFECTED CONTENTS.  ONCE THE EVALUATION OF THE SPILL WAS CONDUCTED THE SET CREW STARTED CLEANUP BY LAYING DOWN OIL ABSORBENT AND BOOMS TO CONTAIN AND SOAK THE MATERIAL RELEASED ONTO THE ASPHALT AND UNDERNEATH THE TRUCK.  THE INSIDE OF THE TRAILER WAS THEN SECURED BY PLACING DOWN BOOMS, OIL PIKC-UP AND CHEM-PADS TO ABSORB MATERIAL RELEASED ONTO TRAILER FLOOR AND OTHER DRUMMED CONTENTS.  AFTER THE ABSORPTION PROCESS FROM MATERIALS USED, THE CREW BEGAN SHOVELING AND SWEEPING THE OIL PICK-UP FROM THE ROADSIDE ASPHALT AND PLACED IT INTO 55 GALLON DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL.  DURING CLEANUP SET, TEXDOT, AND TCEQ ALL TOGETHER AGREED THAT THE MATERIAL WAS NON HAZARDOUS AND THAT THE TRUCK COULD BE MOVED.  MR. DUDLEY REMOVED THE TRUCK AND CONTINUED ITS ROUTE TO SET HOUSTON LOCATION WHERE THE CONTENTS WERE TO BE REMOVED, CLEANED AND KEPT THERE FOR DISPOSAL.  THE SET CREW (UNCAPHER, BODDIE, AND DIXON) STILL OUT AT SPILL SITE, FINISHED SWEEPING THE PAVEMENT AND LOADED UP DRUMS AND SUPPLIES ONTO ER TRUCK.  THEY THEN HEADED TO HOUSTON FACILITY TO DROP OFF DRUMS AND BEGIN CLEANUP OF MR. DUDLEY'S TRUCK TRAILER.  THE SET CREW ARRIVED AT THE HOUSTON YARD, ASSISTED IN UNLOADI

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS TRAVELING SOUTH ON HIGHWAY I55 NEAR NEW MADRID, MO ON 01-28-04.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0845 HOURS AT MILE MARKER 39 OUR TRACTOR/TRAILER LEFT THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE SOUTHBOUND LANE.  OUR DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO REGAIN CONTROL AS THE UNIT WENT INTO THE DITCH.  BOTH UNITS OVERTURNED AND STRUCK THE GROUND.  A WITNESS BEHIND OUR DRIVER THOUGHT THE UNITS HIT "BLACK ICE". OUR DRIVER AND THE WITNESS INDICATED THAT THE TRUCK JERKED CAUSING THE UNITS TO LEAVE THE HIGHWAY.  A COPY OF THE BILL OF LADING AND NON-HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST IS ATTACHED.  THE US DOT CONFIRMATION NUMBER 711736 WAS GIVEN TO US WHEN WE CALLED IN TO REPORT THE SPILL.  MISSOURI DOT INCIDENT #0401280915 GEU.  THE TRAILER HAD A SLIGHT TRICKLE OF LEAKING PRODUCT FROM TWO DOME LIDS WHICH HAD BEEN DAMAGED IN THE ROLLOVER; HOWEVER, THE TANK SKIN WAS NOT RUPTURED.  HULCHER SERVICES INC., KENNETH KNIBBS, HANDLED CLEANUP.  A COPY OF APPROPRIATE BUSINESS CARDS WITH ADDRESSES AND PHONE NUMBERS OF THOSE HELPING WITH THIS INCIDENT IS ATTACHED.

SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT, TOBY TREVETT WAS NOTIFIED THAT A TWENTY FOOT ISO TANK UTCU 459850 WAS IN THE AVONDALE INTERMODAL FACILITY AND WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING.  SAHM TREVETT RESPONDED AND WHILE ENROUTE WAS ADVISED THAT A TRUCK DRIVER MAKING A DELIVERY INTO THE YARD OBSERVED A YELLOW COLORED LIQUID SUBSTANCE UNDER THE ISO TANK.  SAHM TREVETT ARRIVED AT PAD G AND OBSERVED UTCU 459850 TO HAVE A LIGHT YELLOW COLORED POOL OF LIQUID UNDER THE TANK APPROXIMATELY NINE FEET WIDE AND TWENTY FEET LONG.  THERE WAS A SLOW DRIP COMING FROM THE REAR  LIQUID VALVE.  AGENT TREVETT ADVISED RMCC THAT THERE WAS PRODUCT ON THE GROUND AND HE HAD RMCC MAKE ALL THE PROPER NOTIFICATIONS.  US ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, A UP CONTRACTOR, WAS CONTACTED AND RESPONDED. US ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES PERSONNEL WEARING APPROPRIATE PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT INSPECTED THE TANK.  THEY OBSERVED A DRIP COMING FROM THE REAR LIQUID RELEASE VALVE.  THE REAR CAP WAS TURNED A FULL TURN AND A HALF WITH A WRENCH AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  US ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES PERSONNEL ALSO CLEANED UP THE TANK, THE CHASSIS, AND THE SURROUNDING AREA.  ASPHALT IN THE AREA WAS TREATED WITH CITRIC ACID TO NEUTRALIZE ANY REMAINING PRODUCT.  ALL OF THE ABSORBENT PADS AND DEBRIS FROM THE CLEAN UP WERE PLACED INTO FIFTY FIVE GALLON DRUMS, TO BE DISPOSED OF IN ACCORDANCE WITH LOUISIANA STATE REGULATIONS.

column168: UPRR'S RESPONSE MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION CENTER NOTIFIED LANE SEKAVEC, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY OF A REPORTED ODOR FROM A TANK CAR AT THE 18TH STREET YARD IN KANSAS CITY, KS.  MR. SEKAVEC RESPONDED TO THE YARD AND PERFORMED AN INSPECTION OF THE TANK CAR.  WHEN THE COVER ON THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING WAS OPENED, IT WAS VERY APPARENT THAT THE CAR WAS LEAKING FROM THAT AREA BUT IT WAS UNKNOWN WHICH FITTING WAS LEAKING.  ME. SEKAVEC UTILIZED A SULFUR STICK TO TRY TO DETERMINE WHICH FITTING WAS DEFECTIVE BUT THE CONCENTRATION OF THE AMMONIA WAS HIGH ENOUGH THAT THE INDICATION WAS GIVEN THROUGHOUT THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING.  SNOOP WAS ALSO USED IN AN ATTEMPT TO PIN DOWN THE LEAK.  FINALLY, MR. SEKAVEC UTILIZED HIS GLOVED HAND TO FEEL AROUND EACH OF THE FITTINGS AND FOUND A VAPOR LEAK FROM UNDERNEATH THE THERMOMETER WELL CAP, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE CAP WAS ON TIGHT BUT THE LEAK WAS STILL PRESENT, INDICATING THAT THE O-RING WAS PROBABLY DEFECTIVE. FURTHER, THE THERMOMETER WELL DIP TUBE WAS ALSO DEFECTIVE AS INDICATED BY THE VAPOR ESCAPING UP THE DIP TUBE AND OUT THROUGH THE CAP.  RMCC CONTACT CHEMTREC FOR ACCESS TO A REPRESENTATIVE OF THE SHIPPER, KOCH NITROGEN OF ENID, OK.  GAYLENE TRUE CALLED MR. SEKAVEC, AND ADVISED THAT SHE WOULD HAVE THEIR RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, HAZ-MAT RESPONSE, RESPOND TO ASSESS THE CAR. MR. ROBERT MCRAE ARRIVED AND, WITH MR. SEKAVEC,  ASSESSED THE THERMOMETER WELL AND ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN THE CAP DOWN FURTHER WITH NO CHANGE IN THE LEAK.  A FREEZE-PATCH WAS ALSO ATTEMPTED WITH NO SUCCESS.  MR. SEKAVEC AND MR. MCRAE CONCLUDED THAT THE LOAD WOULD HAVE TO BE TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TANK CAR SO THAT THE DEFECTIVE THERMOMETER WELL DIP TUBE COULD BE REPAIRED.  THERE WAS NO WAY TO REMOVE THE CAP FROM THE THERMOMETER WELL TO REPLACE THE DEFECTIVE  O-RING WITH THE CAR UNDER PRESSURE.  THE PRESSURE ON THE CAR WAS 74SIG.  MR. SEKAVEC AND MR. MCRAE MADE SEVERAL CALLS TO FIND A MIDLAND CAPPING KIT TO CAP THE THERMOMETER WELL AND CONTAIN THE LEAKING VAPOR.  AT APPROXIMATELY 2300 HOURS, THEY APPLIED THE MIDLAND CAPPING EQUIPMENT TO PLMX3922 AND WERE ABLE TO STOP THE VAPOR FROM ESCAPING.  THE CAPPING KIT REMAINED IN PLACE UNTIL THE CAR WAS TRANSFERRED.  MR. DEAN DRENT WITH CONTINENTAL NITROGEN ASSISTED TO FINDING ANOTHER TANK CAR IN THE AREA THAT COULD BE USED TO RECEIVE THE LOAD.  UTLX 99003 WAS LOCATED IN KANSAS CITY, MO, AT NEFF YARD AND REROUTED TO 18TH STREET.  MR. MIKE KELLY, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED AS WELL TO TRANSFER THE TANK CAR.  ON JANUARY 12TH, PERSONNEL MET AT 18TH STREET YARD AND THE TRANSFER WAS COMPLETED WITH NO EXCEPTIONS. BOTH CARS WERE INSPECTED TO INSURE THEY WERE IN A CONDITION TO MOVE IN TRANSPORTATION.  ACTING ON CONTINENTAL NITROGEN'S BEHALF, MR. SEKAVEC OBTAINED FROM THE FRA A ONE-TIME MOVEMENT AUTHORITY FOR THE PLMX 3922 TO MOVE TO A REPAIR FACILITY IN NEODESHA, KS.

KIM KEELING, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, REPORTED TANKCAR TCIX 72639, LEAKED FROM THE HEATER COIL LOCATED AT THE BOTTOM OF THE TANKCAR.  MR. KEELING STATED THE TANKCAR WAS LOCATED IN THE ONE SPOT IN THE NORTH PLATTE YARD AND WAS LEAKING AT A RATE OF LESS THAN TEN DRIPS PER HOUR.  HE TESTED THE PRODUCT IN THE HEATER COILS AND FOUND IT TO HAVE A HIGH PH.  MR. KEELING CONTAINED THE LEAK AND CONTACTED THE SHIPPER.  THE SHIPPER ADVISED THAT THE HEATER COILS DID NOT CONTAIN A CORROSION INHIBITOR.  FURTHER DISCUSSION ON THE COLOR OF THE LEAKING MATERIAL DETERMINED THAT THE LEAK APPEARED TO BE THE PRODUCT IN THE TANK CAR.  TWO, TWO INCH CAPS WERE PLACED ON THE OUTLET SIDES OF THE HEATER COILS.  THE SHIPPER REQUESTED THAT THE TANK CAR TO BE RETURNED TO THEIR PLANT IN CORPUS CHRISTI, TX. WHERE IT COULD BE TESTED.  NIKKI, CHEMTREC, WAS NOTIFIED AND PROVIDED REPORT NUMBER OF 01102004022.

column168: DEAN COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, REPORTED TRANSLOADING ENVIRONMENTAL HAD BEEN CONTACTED BY THE LATC RAMP TO INSPECT A LOAD SHIFT IN CONTAINER UESU 218315, PLACARDED CORROSIVE.  INSPECTION DEVELOPED THE LADING TO BE 55 GALLON CLOSED TOP DRUMS ON PALLETS, SEVERAL OF WHICH WERE LEAKING AT THE TIME OF THE INSPECTION.  AS THE PRODUCT WAS MANUFACTURED BY CROMPTON UNIROYAL, CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED TO LOCATE THE SHIPPER THROUGH EVERGREEN, THE RAIL ROAD BILL OF LADING SHIPPER.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH THE SHIPPER TO REMOVE AND INSPECT THE DRUMS.  WHILE REMOVING THE DRUMS, A TOTAL OF SIX DRUMS WERE LOCATED THAT WERE NOTED LEAKING.  THE BOTTOM CHIME OF THE DRUMS SUSTAINED DAMAGE FROM NAILS IN THE PALLETS.  LESS THAN SIX GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS LOST.   AS THE LOAD WAS NOT BLOCKED OR BRACED, THE ENTIRE CONTENTS SHIFTED DURING TRANSIT, CAUSING DAMAGE TO AN ADDITIONAL 38 DRUMS THAT WERE DEEMED UNFIT FOR FURTHER TRANSPORTATION.  THE LEAKING DRUMS WERE PATCHED AND PLACED INTO SALVAGE DRUMS FOR SECUREMENT, ALONG WITH THE 38 DAMAGED DRUMS.  THE ENTIRE LOAD WILL BE PLACED INTO A HIGHWAY TRAILER AND TRANSPORTED BACK TO THE MANUFACTURER PER THEIR REQUEST.

column168: THE MANAGER YARD OPERATIONS IN MISSOURI VALLEY, IA, REPORTED TANKCAR UTLX 15012 SPLASHED SULPHURIC ACID OUT OF THE MANWAY WHILE MOVING IN CARGILL'S YARD IN BLAIR, NE.  NO ACID WAS RELEASED WHILE THE CAR WAS AT REST.  A CONTRACT EMPLOYEE WITH CANAC RAILROAD WAS EXPOSED TO THE SULPHURIC ACID AND TRANSPORTED TO BLAIR HOSPITAL, MARK REIMERS, REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE CARGILL YARD TO INSPECT THE CAR.  MR REIMERS REPORTED THAT INSPECTION OF THE CAR REVEALED THAT ALL THREE MANWAY SWING BOLTS WERE LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT AND THAT THE MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS STRETCHED OUT OF SHAPE AND PROTRUDING FROM UNDER THE LID ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE CAR LEAVING A SIX INCH OPENING INTO THE CAR.  THIS OPENING WAS THE SOURCE OF THE SPLASHING.  MR. REIMERS FASHIONED A GASKET OUT OF GORTEX ROPE AND TIGHTENED DOWN THE MANWAY COVER SO THAT THE CAR COULD BE SAFELY MOVED INTO THE CARGILL PLANT FOR OFF LOADING.

column168: ON JANUARY 5, 2004 AT 7:35 AM, WE HAD A TDI (TOLUENE DIISOCYANATE) SPILL AT OUR RAIL DOCK AREA.  WE HAD BEEN UNLOADING A TDI RAILCAR FOR APPROXIMATELY 1.5 HOURS WHEN A PIGTAIL PRESSURE GAUGE SIPHON CONNECTION ON THE DISCHARGE SIDE OF THE UNLOADING PUMP BROKE.  THE CHEMICAL UNLOADING OPERATOR WAS OUTSIDE ON THE TANK TRUCK UNLOADING PAD PUMPING OUT COLLECTED RAINWATER FROM THE SUMP.  OUR LOCAL PIPING CONTRACTOR WAS ALSO IN THE AREA.  AFTER HITTING THE EMERGENCY STOP FOR THE TDI UNLOADING SYSTEM, THE CHEMICAL UNLOADING OPERATOR IMMEDIATELY CLIMBED TO THE TOP OF THE PRESSURIZED RAIL CAR AND SHUT OFF THE SUPPLY VALVE TO THE PUMP, THE PIPING CONTRACTOR SHUT OFF THE SUCTION VALVE ON THE PUMP AND THE TDI HAD BEEN SPILLED ON THE ADJACENT PLATFORM AND IN THE RAIL DOCK PIT OVER THE COURSE OF 1 TO 2 MINUTES.  WE EVACUATED PERSONNEL FROM THE AREA AND THE PLANT ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGER BEGAN TDI MONITORING IN THE SURROUNDING AREAS.  THE CHEMICAL SPILL TEAM THEN POURED TDI AND NEUTRALIZER ON THE PLATFORM, PUMP, PIPES AND IN THE PIT.  THE AREA WAS MARKED WITH CORDON CAUTION TAPE AND PORTABLE FLOOR FANS WERE BROUGHT TO THE DOCK TO DIRECT THE TDI AND NEUTRALIZER VAPORS AWAY FROM THE SURROUNDING WORK AREAS.  WE GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 2 DRUMS OF CLEAN UP WASTE (ABSORBENT MATERIALS, GLOVES, ETC.) THAT HAVE BEEN LABELED AS HAZARDOUS WASTE AND PLACED IN THE CENTRAL ACCUMULATION AREA.  I PLACED SPILL NOTIFICATION CALLS TO THE FOLLOW AGENCIES: NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (NRC) AT 7:43 AM (REPORT NO. 709677), STATE EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMMISSION (SERC) AT 7:54 AM, AND ENVIRONMENTAL COORDINATOR FOR THE CITY OF RUSSELLVILLE AT 7:58 AM.  SINCE THE SPILLED TDI DID NOT ULTIMATELY LEAVE THE FACILITY AND ENTER ANY WATERWAYS, OUTSIDE ASSISTANCE FROM THESE AGENCIES WAS NOT NECESSARY OR REQUESTED.  ALTHOUGH THE RELEASE WAS IN EXCESS OF THE REPORTABLE QUANTITY (RQ) OF 100 POUNDS, THE MATERIAL REMAINED WITHIN THE BUILDING DURING THE SPILL AND CLEANUP AND DID NOT ENTER THE ENVIRONMENT.  UNDER CERCLA (COMPREHENSIVE ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE, COMPENSATION AND LIABILITY ACT OF 1980) AND EPCRA (EMERGENCY PLANNING AND COMMUNITY RIGHT-TO-KNOW ACT OF 1986), THE SPILL WAS EXCLUDED FROM REPORTING AS DESCRIBED IN 40 CFR 302.3 AND 40 CFR 355.40 (A)(2)(I).  AT THE TIME OF THE SPILL, I COULD NOT ABSOLUTELY MAKE THE DETERMINATION THAT NO TDI HAD LEFT THE BUILDING, SO I DECIDED THE PRUDENT COURSE OF ACTION WAS TO IMMEDIATELY REPORT THE INCIDENT TO THE APPROPRIATE AGENCIES.  IT APPEARED THAT THE FAILURE OF THE SIPHON CONNECTION WHICH HAD BROKEN IN THE PIPE THREADS WAS MOST LIKELY DUE TO FATIGUE FROM PUMP VIBRATION.  IT WAS REPLACED WITH A SECTION OF FLEXIBLE STAINLESS STEEL BRAIDED TEFLON LINED HIGH PRESSURE HOSE TO ISOLATE THE GAUGE AND DAMPEN THIS VIBRATION.  THE PUMPING SYSTEM WILL BE MONITORED TO DETERMINE IF OTHER MODIFICATIONS ARE NECESSARY TO REDUCE THE LIKELIHOOD OF OTHER VIBRATION RELATED PROBLEMS. SUBSEQUENTLY TDI MONITORING BY WADE INDICATED ACCEPTABLE TDI CONCENTRATIONS (2 TO 3 PPB) IN THE SURROU
